snippet.textDisplay:
The first estimate of inflation doesn't take into account international conversion rates. Superstar saga uses beanbean coins for a majority of the game rather than mushroom kingdom coins, and the exchange rate changes over the course of the game. At the beginning, it's 10(mushroom):1(beanbean), but later on in the game it's 99,999,999,999,999(mushroom):99(beanbean). With an exchange rate that varied, it's likely one of the economies is crashing, leading to massive inflation in the mushroom kingdom in absence of its regency - but conversely that means Mario has investments in a stable international market.

Tl:Dr - Mario is tax sheltering using the beanbean kingdom

snippet.textDisplay: Actually, the situation may be worse. You see, in Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga, our heroes find themselves in the Beanbean Kingdom, a kingdom that uses a different form of currency, the beanbean coin. This coin, at the beggining of the game, is said to have a conversion rate of 1 beanbean coin per 100 coins (Mushroom Kingdom's currency). That means that any value BDG reached using the game as a basis, is actually only 1% of what Mario would really need in his home kingdom, which isn't the best thing for our mushroom loving friend.

snippet.textDisplay: I love Brian's videos, but one thing REALLY bothered me about this one and that would be that he uses superstar saga as his reference point for inflation. You use beanbean kingdom coins in that one, which, thanks to google for reminding me, is a 10:1 conversion rate with mushroom kingdom coins. So the prices for items in superstar saga are totally irrelevant to what mario is used to spending! Maybe bowser's inside story would be a better reference point since it takes place in the mushroom kingdom? Idk Im not a research kind of guy haha
